Hypothesis: High editing, no knockout, disrupting last 4 amino acids before a stop codon.
No editing, no knockout, probably wouldn't do anything given after stop codon
High editing, high knockout, may introduce a later splice site that would induce premature stop in exon 1, or it skips the vast majority of the protein sequence.
No editing, no knockout
Not strictly a splice guide, vast majority of edit is a pmSTOP, likely inducing NMD because only 4 amino acids left
Low editing, but consistent with protein loss.
Medium editing, medium knockout, consistent, no clear effect, probably an NMD mechanism. Very early.
Low editing, proportional knockout, pmSTOP induction
High editing, no knockout. Does not appear subject to NMD in constrast to the B2m edit. Disrupting this ITAM after the first YxxL motif doesn't appear to have any effect.

High editing, hairthin knockout. In the last exon so no NMD would occur. THis does disrupt the middle of the ITAM motif, which may or may not produce a functional knockout of the protein. It would be interesting to test if this can still signal.

High editing, no knockout. Edits after the last ITAM. only truncates the protein by 5 amino acids, so not really suprising that no knockout occurs. Dispensible for CD3 complex localization to the surface. Further studies for functional signalling would need to be assessed. Duplicate guide

Good editing, good knockout. Early on in gene. Would trigger skipping of the entire immunoglobulin domain and maintain the reading frame. May suggest that the immunoglobulin domain interaction is required for receptor surface localization.

Good editing, good knockout. Early on in gene. May trigger skipping of the entire immunoglobulin domain and maintain the reading frame if the donor induces a change similar to TRAC. May suggest that the immunoglobulin domain interaction is required for receptor surface localization. Downstream cryptic splice donors also maintain the reading frame. There is a stop codon in frame if it reads into the exon. Mainly potential options for knockout.
No editing, no knockout.
Good editing, good knockout. Very early premature stop.
moderate editing, moderation proportional knockout.

Low editing, low proportional knockout. Likely induces a pmSTOP and causes NMD. interestingly this is located before the other ITAMs. Would be interesting to know if that inhibits surface localization.
Low editing, no knockout. Doesn't appear to have an effect on localization, but it could. Not enough information. In an ITAM.

moderate editing, no knockout. Technically interupts the distal part of the ITAM motif. Barely though. moves the stop codon a few amino acids earlier than WT stop codon. Consistent with idea of not really effectiing the molecule.
Good editing, no knockout. In middle of IG domain. Would skip 6 amino acids and still retain the frame. Likely creates a full length functional variant.
Good editing, good knockout.
Low editing, low knockout. appears proportional. Maintains the frame when skipped. If skipped it will knockout the transmembrane domain. Reclassify guide as one targetting the transmembrane domain.
Good editing, good knockout.

Moderate editing, proportional knockout. Targets an ITAM. Cryptic donor may disrupt frame. May retain the intron and lead to a stop codon. Would introduce a frame shift if exon is skipped. Knockout is probably due to an NMD mechanism, unless the ITAM appears essential in this molecule. I believe it is among the most important of the complex.

Good editing, does not knockout. Probably because it targets an exon before the ATG codon. Therefore at worst the intron is retained and then the start codon begins. Demonstrates the need to target after the start codon with this approach.

Good editing, proportional knockout. A little lower in donor B. Targets an ITAM. Cryptic donor may disrupt frame. May retain the intron and lead to a stop codon. High editing, proportional knockout. Likely has a cryptic splice site that either introduces a frameshift or a pmSTOP. Targets very early on in the protein. Best guide to CD3E.

Moderate editing, the knockout appears lower than expected. Introduces a premature stop at the base of the intracellular domain. No editing, no knockout.
